result.execSummary:
The defendant Albert L Jones was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver Heroin (<3g), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(d)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Albert L Jones in court with attorney James Edgar Toran.  Antonella Aleman appeared for the State of Wisconsin on behalf of Laura Crivello.    Sentencing proceeded.  

Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 6 YEARS, with credit for 2 DAYS time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.  If defendant is revoked, same conditions apply to extended supervision as conditions of probation, except for the condition time.
If revoked, NO CONDITION TIME

The Court STAYED this sentence and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 4 YEARS with the following conditions:  

- Serve 1 YEAR UP FRONT CONDITION TIME CONSECUTIVE, in the House of Correction - with huber for work  a maxium of hours of TWO JOBS, meeting with agent, and treatment.  

                           ***DEFENDANT TAKEN INTO CUSTODY.***

- AODA assessment, and comply with any recommended treatment.
- Absolute sobriety, no alcohol, no controlled substances without a valid prescription, with random drug tests and breathlyzers.  Defendant should be tested randomly.
- Complete a cognitive intervention therapy program.
-  Maintain full time employment. 
- Comply and complete programs and or treatment recommended by agent.
- Pay restitution for the "buy money" in the amount of $1025.00 to Milwaukee Police Department by making regular monthly payments. Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means, at no cost to the Milwaukee Police Department.
-  50 Hours of Community Service
-  Pay Child Support
- No association with known drug users or dealers, and no contact at any place where illegal drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged, or distributed.
- Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample, and pay all MANDATORY COURT costs, fees, surcharges, and assessments, to be paid while on probation or serve 10 days in the HOC. 
- Pay all supervision fees.  Defendant to make regular payments.

Defendant Albert L Jones in court with attorney James Edgar Toran.  Karen Ann Loebel appeared for the State of Wisconsin for Laura Crivello.

AS TO COUNT 2:
Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of State, Court ordered COUNT 2 dismissed, and read in for sentencing.  

AS TO COUNT 1:
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgment of conviction entered.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court also advises defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  
Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing.
Case adjourned for sentencing on 6/17/2014 at 8:30 am, branch 3.  PSI ordered signed and filed.  Court reminds defendant to continue and comply with Justice Point, and to not use or possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription.
